{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1f4cab70-ac8e-41b7-a222-5e306f77329a","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID format** to fully-qualified names. Azure DevOps matches history by test ID, so every test looks \"new.\" You can restore the old IDs by adding this to your `.runsettings`:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\nOr set the project property:\n\n```xml\n<TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is **no longer tied to any specific test** (class init runs once before all tests). Accessing `TestName`, `TestResultsDirectory`, etc. now throws `InvalidOperationException`.\n\nYour code on **line 13** hits this directly:\n\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // throws in v4\n```\n\n**Fix:** Remove the `TestName` access from `ClassInit`. If you need per-test names, move that logic to `[TestInitialize]` or use the instance `TestContext` property:\n\n```csharp\n[TestInitialize]\npublic void TestInit()\n{\n    var testName = TestContext.TestName; // works fine here\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` on doubles** | Now uses bitwise comparison; `Assert.AreEqual(0.0, -0.0)` **fails**. Use the overload with a `delta` parameter. |\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | Implicit conversions (e.g., `int` → `long`) that worked in v3 may now fail. Match types exactly. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Read-only in assembly/class-init contexts. |\n| **Parallel execution** | Class-level parallelism is now opt-in per class via `[Parallelizable]`. Review if you relied on the old defaults. |\n| **`[DeploymentItem]`** | Stricter path resolution; relative paths resolve differently. |\n| **`[Timeout]` attribute** | Now applies to the test method only (not setup/cleanup). Long `[TestInitialize]` won't be covered. |\n\nIf you'd like, I can patch your `SetupTests.cs` and `.csproj` to fix both issues.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"053741ac-4f09-48d1-aa6e-fa152fc8e89b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has upgraded to MSTest v4.1.0 and is experiencing two issues:\n\n1. Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps (lost history)\n2. `TestContext.TestName` throwing in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nLet me provide a comprehensive answer about known MSTest v4 breaking changes.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Fully Qualified Test IDs** - MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are generated. They now use fully qualified names by default, which means Azure DevOps sees them as completely new tests (no history match). This is the cause of the \"brand new tests\" issue.\n\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize** - The `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` isn't tied to any specific test method, so accessing `TestContext.TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException` since class initialization runs before any individual test executes.\n3. **Other breaking changes** - `[DeploymentItem]` behavior has shifted, `TestContext.Properties` lost write access in certain scenarios, and the `TestContext` instances passed to `[AssemblyInitialize]` and `[ClassInitialize]` are now different types than before.\n\nThere are also `DataRow` attribute changes and parallel execution defaults that may differ, so I should provide a comprehensive answer about what's actually changed in MSTest v4.","outputTokens":1004},"id":"763477d1-a6fa-4191-afb1-5756a0654ae5","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:03:26.957Z","parentId":"b4d26d50-557a-4aa6-b491-cdb7ffc9fd52"}
